Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// In your MCP server project, inject HttpClient via constructor
public class WeatherTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;
    public WeatherTool(HttpClient httpClient) => _httpClient = httpClient;

    public async Task<string> GetForecastAsync(string city)
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync($"https://api.weather.com/{city}");
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
```

**3. Use a mock `HttpMessageHandler` to fake API responses**

```csharp
public class FakeHandler : DelegatingHandler
{
    private readonly HttpResponseMessage _response;
    public FakeHandler(HttpResponseMessage response) =>
        _response = response;

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct) =>
        Task.FromResult(_response);
}
```

**4. Write tests against your tools**

```csharp
public class WeatherToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_ReturnsExpectedData()
    {
        var fakeResponse = new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK)
        {
            Content = new StringContent("{\"temp\": 72}")
        };
        var client = new HttpClient(new FakeHandler(fakeResponse));
        var tool = new WeatherTool(client);

        var result = await tool.GetForecastAsync("seattle");

        Assert.Contains("72", result);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task GetForecast_Handles500()
    {
        var fakeResponse = new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError);
        var client = new HttpClient(new FakeHandler(fakeResponse));
        var tool = new WeatherTool(client);

        await Assert.ThrowsAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => tool.GetForecastAsync("seattle"));
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

- **Inject `HttpClient`** (or `IHttpClientFactory`) — never `new` it inside tools
- **Fake at the `HttpMessageHandler` level** — this avoids mocking framework dependencies and tests real serialization/deserialization
- **One test class per tool** — keeps tests focused
- For more complex scenarios, consider [WireMock.Net](https://github.com/WireMock-Net/WireMock.Net) which spins up a local HTTP server with canned responses
